Rust offers different ways to initialize  variables. Recently, I had to create a runtime-initialized variable: existing approaches don't work in this case. I want to describe multiple ways to achieve it in this post.The Rust language allows you to create constants. Two keywords are available:  and .Sometimes a certain value is used many times throughout a program, and it can become inconvenient to copy it over and over. What’s more, it’s not always possible or desirable to make it a variable that gets carried around to each function that needs it. In these cases, the  keyword provides a convenient alternative to code duplication:A static item is a value which is valid for the entire duration of your program (a  lifetime).On the surface,  items seem very similar to : both contain a value, both require type annotations and both can only be initialized with constant functions and values. However,  are notably different in that they represent a location in memory. That means that you can have references to  items and potentially even modify them, making them essentially global variables.Static items do not call  at the end of the program.There are two types of  items: those declared in association with the  keyword and those without.None of the above work with .Trying to compile the previous line returns the following:error[E0015]: cannot call non-const fn `regex::Regex::new` in constants
  |
6 | const REGEXP_WAREHOUSE_ENDPOINT: Regex = Regex::new(r"^WAREHOUSE__(?<index>\d)__ENDPOINT.*").unwrap();
  |                                          ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
  |
  = note: calls in constants are limited to constant functions, tuple structs and tuple variants
The same happens with if we change  to .error[E0015]: cannot call non-const fn `regex::Regex::new` in statics
 --> src/config.rs:6:43
  |
6 | static REGEXP_WAREHOUSE_ENDPOINT: Regex = Regex::new(r"^WAREHOUSE__(?<index>\d)__ENDPOINT.*").unwrap();
  |                                           ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
  |
  = note: calls in statics are limited to constant functions, tuple structs and tuple variants
We need a  variable for the . Neither  nor  work; time to search for something else.When you need something, there's a high chance somebody required it before. If lucky, they created a crate for it. Case in point, the  crate provides a solution.A macro for declaring lazily evaluated statics in Rust.Using this macro, it is possible to have statics that require code to be executed at runtime in order to be initialized. This includes anything requiring heap allocations, like vectors or hash maps, as well as anything that requires non-const function calls to be computed.The usage is straightforward: we wrap the  declaration in a macro.We achieved what we wanted to. Yet, we can do better.Rust 1.80 adds .  is a built-in exact replacement for the  macro.

