But functions  take input. And when they do, the input goes inside those parentheses.fn main() {
    greet("Kehn");
}

fn greet(name: &str) {
    println!("👋🏼 Hello, {}!", name);
}
Rust requires all instructions to run from inside a function, and that function must start from .
that's why we had to write main and call the greet function inside it firstIn the line , you are calling the function , and passing  as the input to it.🧠 Let's imagine the compiler is a robot that follows rules:It  read your code from top to bottom like a ."Where is ? That’s my  point. I’ll start there and run whatever is inside it."If you just write  of , Rust gets confused:❌ "Wait, when should I run this? How? I don't just run random lines of code lying outside — that's illegal in "•  is  down belowfn greet(name: &str) {
    println!("👋🏼 Hello, {}!", name);
}
— It's like saying: "Here's how you greet someone."• But unless someone  it from inside  (the starting point), it  anything.Just  greet() doesn't tell the computer to run it. It's just there, waiting to be used.Now let's dive into Example 1  by •  → This means function.•  → The name of the function. Rust always looks for  first. It's the entry point.•  → These are parentheses. This function takes no input.•  → This starts the body of the function. All the code that the function runs will go inside these curly braces .


  We’re telling Rust: "Hey, this is the main starting point. Whatever is inside these curly braces should run first."
•  → This is the name of a function we’re calling (we'll define it later).•  → We're passing a value — the text  — into that function.•  → This ends the line. Rust needs this semicolon to know the instruction is complete.


  Inside , we are saying: “Hey Rust, please run the greet function and give it the word .”
This ends the  function. It says: “That’s it for main. No more instructions here.”✅ :  → Again, this is a  → This is the name of the function. → We are saying:This function takes one parameter called name, and it must be a  (a bit of text).•  → This is the  the function will use.•  → This is the  of that variable. It means: “a reference to a string” → like  or .•  → Starts the body of the greet function.


  We’re defining a function called greet that expects a name as input. Then, we’ll do something with that name — like printing it out.
✅ :     println!("👋🏼 Hello, {}!", name);•  → This is a macro that prints a line of text to the screen.•  → Means it's a macro, not a normal function. Macros do some extra behind-the-scenes magic.•  → This is the text we want to print. The {} is a placeholder — we’ll fill it in.•  → We are saying: “Put the value of name (which is ) inside the {}.”•  → End of the instruction.Because we passed  into greet, and greet used  to insert that value.This ends the  function.Don't worry if you're still confused about lines 4 and 5 – we'll go through them in more detail in the next episodes. says: “Call the  function and give it .”Rust jumps to  and sets name = . prints:
👋🏼 Hello, Kehn!

Anatomy of a Rust programSo, let's say you want to write a Rust program that printsThis is an example of what that code would look like:fn main() {
println!("Hello, world!");
}
Running this code ☝🏼 will produce the desired output. But why didn't we just write Hey,  on my screen and it works? Why do we have to follow the format shown above?I'll explain the code above bit by bit, detailing what each element means and does..• fn is short for function.
• A function is a block of code that  an .• Not all code is a function.
• However, the starting point of a program must be a function, and that function is called "."•It's the . The beginning. The commander-in-chief.
•If you remove , Rust won’t know where to start and will throw an error:error: cannot find function `main` in this crate
Rust is a  and strongly typed systems language, and it needs a clearly defined  and .the compiler wouldn’t know:• Where to begin execution
• How to manage scope, stack, variables, lifetimes, etc.Rust is optimized for , , and , so structure matters a lot.We'll talk about main in the next episode. Stay rusty 😉🦀
